 Technology, Modernisation, and Development -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite issues associated with the digital divide, mobile telephony is growing on the continent and the rise of smartphones has given citizens easy access to social networking sites. But the digital divide, which mostly reflects on one's race, gender, socioeconomic status or geographical location, stands in the way of digital progress. What opportunities are available to tame digital disparities? How are different societies in Africa handling digital problems? What innovative methods are being used to provide citizens with access to critical information that can help improve their lives? Experiences from various locations in several sub-Saharan African countries have been carefully selected in this collection with the aim of providing an updated account on the digital divide and its impact in Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDigital dividezAfrica. 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspects. 4aContemporary Society. 4aDigital and Social Media. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh  aDigital divide, Africa, technology, social media.1 aAnyanwu, Chika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrouwer, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButhelezi, Mbalenhle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChitanana, Tenford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalvit, Lorenzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJjuuko, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaram, Bescha